# Prompt 0 — Project Foundation & Master Planning

Use this once when starting a brand-new project.

After the project foundation is created:

 - Save the generated Project Continuation Plan.
 - From then on, switch to your normal workflow (Prompt 1 → Prompt 2 → Prompt 3...).

---

```
Act as a Principal Software Engineer, AI Platform Architect, Senior SDET, Software Architect, Engineering Manager, Technical Recruiter, and Product Designer.

We are starting a brand-new long-term software project.

Project Name:

Enterprise AI Testing Platform

This project will become my flagship engineering portfolio and will continuously evolve for the next 1–2+ years.

The objective is NOT to build a demo.

The objective is to build a production-quality, enterprise-grade platform that demonstrates senior-level engineering skills across AI, software testing, automation, system design, and software architecture.

The platform should be designed from the beginning for long-term extensibility.

Future technologies should be easy to add without requiring major redesign.

Assume:

- I prefer open-source and free technologies whenever practical.
- Paid services may be supported later through provider abstractions.
- The architecture should support replacing any major component without affecting the rest of the platform.
- Maintainability is more important than quickly shipping features.
- Backward compatibility should be preserved whenever practical.

The platform should eventually support areas such as:

- LLM Testing
- Prompt Testing
- AI Evaluation
- RAG Evaluation
- Agent Evaluation
- Multi-Provider LLM Support
- Multi-Provider Embeddings
- Multiple Vector Databases
- Hybrid Retrieval
- Knowledge Graph Retrieval
- Playwright AI Testing
- API Testing
- Performance Testing
- AI Observability
- AI Security Testing
- Benchmarking
- Synthetic Test Generation
- Dataset Management
- Experiment Tracking
- Reporting
- CI/CD
- Plugin Architecture

Before suggesting implementation, design the project as if it were being developed by an enterprise engineering team.

Generate a complete Project Foundation document.

The document should include:

# Vision

# Goals

# Non-Goals

# Target Users

# Long-Term Roadmap

# Engineering Philosophy

# Technology Selection

Explain why every major technology was selected.

Include alternatives that were considered.

# Repository Structure

Design a scalable repository suitable for years of development.

# Architecture

Design a modular enterprise architecture.

Use diagrams where appropriate.

# Design Patterns

Explain which patterns should be used throughout the project and why.

# Module Responsibilities

Clearly define the responsibility of every major module.

# Configuration Strategy

Explain how configuration should work.

# Provider Strategy

Explain how provider abstraction should work.

# Plugin Strategy

Explain how optional components should integrate.

# Testing Strategy

Design a complete testing strategy.

Include:

- Unit Testing
- Integration Testing
- End-to-End Testing
- AI Evaluation
- Regression Testing
- Performance Testing

# Development Workflow

Explain the recommended Git workflow.

Explain how feature branches should be organized.

Assume I will use the Engineering Project Workflow Prompts repository.

# Coding Standards

Define coding conventions.

# Documentation Standards

Explain what documentation should exist.

# Release Strategy

Design an enterprise release strategy.

# Technical Debt Strategy

Explain how technical debt should be handled.

# Future Expansion

Design the architecture so future technologies can be added without major redesign.

# Risks

Identify architectural risks.

Recommend mitigation strategies.

# Recommended Phase Roadmap

Break the project into logical implementation phases.

Each phase should contain:

- Objective
- Deliverables
- Dependencies
- Estimated complexity
- Portfolio value

The roadmap should maximize long-term engineering quality instead of short-term feature count.

Finally, generate the initial Master Project Continuation Plan.

This continuation plan will become the single source of truth for all future development.

Do not generate implementation code.

Focus entirely on designing the project correctly before implementation begins.
```
